Data Description

Description

fMRI data consists of location and stimulus timing related to percieved pain. Stimulus was applied for 32 seconds with 32 seconds waiting period. The sampling rate was one measurement of BOLD (blood oxigenation-level dependent) intensity every 2 seconds for 256 seconds (n = 128). The number of subjects under each condition varies.

Details

The signal was measured in 9 brain Locations (L): [1] Cortex 1: Primary Somatosensory, Contralateral (pSS(C)), [2] Cortex 2: Primary Somatosensory, Ipsilateral (pSS(I)), [3] Cortex 3: Secondary Somatosensory, Contralateral (sSS(C)), [4] Cortex 4: Secondary Somatosensory, Ipsilateral (sSS(I)), [5] Caudate (Cau), [6] Thalamus 1: Contralateral (Tha(C)), [7] Thalamus 2: Ipsilateral (Tha(I)), [8] Cerebellum 1: Contralateral(Crb(C))
*[9] Cerebellum 2: Ipsilateral (Crb(I)).

The stimuli (T) with the number of respective sujects: [1] Awake-Brush (5 subjects), [2] Awake-Heat (4 subjects), [3] Awake-Shock (5 subjects), [4] Low-Brush (3 subjects), [5] Low-Heat (5 subjects), and [6] Low-Shock (4 subjects).

Example: fmri$L1T6 (as well as fmri[[6]]) (Location 1, Treatment 6) will show the data for Cortex 1: Primary Somatosensory, Contralateral location with Low-Shock (4 subjects) treatment

Data Exploration

plotting multiple locations for the same stimulus data

Awake-Heat

par(mfrow=c(3,2))
#Explore T2 on all of the cortex zones
ts.plot(as.ts(fmri$L1T2), col=3:7, main="Cortex 1: Primary Somatosensory, Contralateral", ylab="BOLD", xlab="Time (1 pt = 2sec)")
ts.plot(as.ts(fmri$L2T2), col=3:7, main="Cortex 2: Primary Somatosensory, Ipsilateral", ylab="BOLD", xlab="Time (1 pt = 2sec)")
ts.plot(as.ts(fmri$L3T2),col=3:7, main="Cortex 3: Secondary Somatosensory, Contralateral", ylab="BOLD", xlab="Time (1 pt = 2sec)")
ts.plot(as.ts(fmri$L4T2),col=3:7, main="Cortex 4: Secondary Somatosensory, Ipsilateral", ylab="BOLD", xlab="Time (1 pt = 2sec)")

ts.plot(as.ts(fmri$L8T2),col=3:7, main="Cerebellum 1: Contralateral", ylab="BOLD", xlab="Time (1 pt = 2sec)")
ts.plot(as.ts(fmri$L9T2),col=3:7, main="Cerebellum 2: Ipsilateral", ylab="BOLD", xlab="Time (1 pt = 2sec)")

Observations: In response to Awake-Heat stimulation * Both Contralateral Cortex zone show potential strong correlation and cyclic increase in BOLD response in 16, 45, 77 and 110 sec that resembles a gradual addaptation to the stimulus. * On the other hand, the Primary Ipsilateral zone reacts with a steady increase, with a max at the 32 sec of the stimulus during the first application, however the second stimulus produces two picks: 32 sec and 64. * The secondary Ipsilateral zone follows the Contralateral zone pattern with higher variability of the BOLD response signal * Cerebellum exibits response to the stimulus similar to the Cortex Secondary zone with slightly less pronounced cyclic variations

Data transformation:

Current data is per test subject that makes it harder for analysis. Aggregation by mean would clarify the trends of the data. Log transformation is not appropriate since the range and variancies of BOLD values are relatively small and do not exhibit rapid growth pattern over time.

#Install corrplot

## corrplot 0.84 loaded

Correlation coefficients are colored according to the value. Correlation matrix can be also reordered according to the degree of association between variables. The function corrplot() takes the correlation matrix as the first argument. The second argument (type=“upper”) is used to display only the upper triangular of the correlation matrix.

Let’s combine correlogram with the significance test. We’ll use the result generated with rcorr() function [in Hmisc package]

Insignificant correlations are leaved blank Order method of the correlation matrix (“original” for original order (default), “AOE” for the angular order of the eigenvectors, “FPC” for the first principal component order, “hclust” for the hierarchical clustering order, “alphabet” for alphabetical order)

Let’s check if it is White Noise.

WN assumptions:

95% of values ~= 0 and lay inside the blue lines

They should be uncorrelated

They should have mean zero

Useful properties (for computing prediction intervals) ### They should have constant variance ### They should be normally distributed

Use Ljung-Box test to check for WN

The Ljung-Box test considers the first h autocorrelation values together.

Box.test(fmri_SShock1, lag = 16, fitdf = 0, type = "Lj")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  fmri_SShock1
## X-squared = 29.947, df = 16, p-value = 0.01828

p-value = 0.01828 indicates the data are probably White Noise.

Summary:

We can test for white noise by looking at an ACF plot or by doing a Ljung-Box test
